the entire Radcliffe

00:00:52.150 --> 00:00:54.470
Institute with us today.

00:00:54.470 --> 00:00:57.130
I appreciate the
generosity of everyone,

00:00:57.130 --> 00:01:00.970
which makes all that we do
here at Radcliffe possible.

00:01:00.970 --> 00:01:04.150
And I'm especially
pleased to welcome members

00:01:04.150 --> 00:01:07.480
of both of Radcliffe's
Advisory Councils,

00:01:07.480 --> 00:01:10.300
our Deans Advisory Council
and the Schlesinger Library

00:01:10.300 --> 00:01:11.110
Council.

00:01:11.110 --> 00:01:14.470
And I am so glad that you
could all be with us today.

00:01:14.470 --> 00:01:18.880
Radcliffe is dedicated to
inquiry and research that

00:01:18.880 --> 00:01:21.370
takes place beyond
the curriculum

00:01:21.370 --> 00:01:25.450
and across the boundaries of
academic disciplines we bring

00:01:25.450 --> 00:01:28.870
together scholars and
scientists, artists

00:01:28.870 --> 00:01:32.230
and public intellectuals
from around the world

00:01:32.230 --> 00:01:34.570
to share their work
with each other

00:01:34.570 --> 00:01:38.350
and with a broad,
interested public like you.

00:01:38.350 --> 00:01:41.440
Today we are here to look
at a very different time

00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:43.990
from an unconventional angle.

00:01:43.990 --> 00:01:46.000
And we could have
no better guide

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:48.580
than Jane Kamensky,
my fellow historian

00:01:48.580 --> 00:01:50.530
and Radcliffe colleague.

00:01:50.530 --> 00:01:54.970
Jane earned her BA and her
PhD at Yale University.

00:01:54.970 --> 00:01:56.650
She taught in the
History Department

00:01:56.650 --> 00:02:00.250
at Brandeis for 21 years,
including doing two stints

00:02:00.250 --> 00:02:01.567
as Department Chair.

00:02:01.567 --> 00:02:02.275
And she survived.

00:02:02.275 --> 00:02:03.910
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:03.910 --> 00:02:08.650
She also served on the core
faculty in Women's Gender

00:02:08.650 --> 00:02:11.890
and Sexuality Studies at
Brandeis while she was there.

00:02:11.890 --> 00:02:15.070
During the 2014-15
academic year,

00:02:15.070 --> 00:02:18.760
Jane was the Mary L.
Cornille Distinguished

00:02:18.760 --> 00:02:20.710
Visiting Professor
at the Newhouse

00:02:20.710 --> 00:02:24.190
Center for the Humanities
at Wellesley College.

00:02:24.190 --> 00:02:27.520
In 2015, Jane came
to Harvard to serve

00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:31.000
as the Faculty Director of
Radcliffe Schlesinger Library

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:33.430
and as a member of the
History Department.

00:02:33.430 --> 00:02:36.940
But Jane's connections to
Radcliffe go back even further.

00:02:36.940 --> 00:02:41.250
We are pleased that Jane was
a Radcliffe fellow in 2006-07,

00:02:41.250 --> 00:02:45.040
and a Bunting fellow
a decade before that.

00:02:45.040 --> 00:02:49.190
All of Jane's work from her
scholarship, to her teaching,

00:02:49.190 --> 00:02:52.030
to her leadership of
the Schlesinger Library

00:02:52.030 --> 00:02:58.350
is marked by innovation,
dynamism, and creativity.

00:02:58.350 --> 00:03:01.530
These were the qualities
that greatly inspired us

00:03:01.530 --> 00:03:05.230
when Jane interviewed for the
position of Faculty Director.

00:03:05.230 --> 00:03:08.190
And in her first year
and a half on the job,

00:03:08.190 --> 00:03:10.800
she has brought them to
bear on her ambitious vision

00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:12.510
for the library.

00:03:12.510 --> 00:03:15.270
Together with Executive
Director Marilyn Dunn,

00:03:15.270 --> 00:03:17.730
Jane has undertaken
impressive efforts

00:03:17.730 --> 00:03:21.030
to diversify the library's
collections, seeking

00:03:21.030 --> 00:03:25.530
to represent a fuller spectrum
of women's experiences

00:03:25.530 --> 00:03:28.830
across class, race,
political perspective,

00:03:28.830 --> 00:03:33.120
sexual orientation, religious
experience, and more.

00:03:33.120 --> 00:03:35.130
And under her
leadership, with the help

00:03:35.130 --> 00:03:37.680
of the Schlesinger's
very able staff,

00:03:37.680 --> 00:03:40.500
the library is fast
establishing itself

00:03:40.500 --> 00:03:44.670
as a pioneer in new ways of
using rich manuscript archives

00:03:44.670 --> 00:03:46.650
in teaching and learning.

00:03:46.650 --> 00:03:48.660
No surprise that
it is increasingly

00:03:48.660 --> 00:03:52.110
being sought out by professors
from across Harvard schools

00:03:52.110 --> 00:03:53.640
and departments.

00:03:53.640 --> 00:03:56.760
Jane's innovation,
dynamism, and creativity

00:03:56.760 --> 00:04:00.240
have likewise established
her as a leading historian

00:04:00.240 --> 00:04:03.730
of early America and an
interdisciplinary scholar who

00:04:03.730 --> 00:04:06.810
has written on colonial history,
the history of women, gender,

00:04:06.810 --> 00:04:10.290
and the family, and the
history of capitalism.

00:04:10.290 --> 00:04:13.890
She has also ranged beyond the
conventional by coauthoring

00:04:13.890 --> 00:04:17.970
an historical novel and
co-founding a digital journal

00:04:17.970 --> 00:04:21.300
called Common-Place: The
Interactive Journal of Early

00:04:21.300 --> 00:04:23.370
American Life, and
these are both projects

00:04:23.370 --> 00:04:26.790
that she did in partnership with
fellow Harvard historian Jill

00:04:26.790 --> 00:04:28.350
Lepore.

00:04:28.350 --> 00:04:31.890
Interdisciplinary creativity
marks all of Jane's books,

00:04:31.890 --> 00:04:35.850
along with her tireless
research, her eye for just

00:04:35.850 --> 00:04:39.480
the right detail and her
elegant writer's voice,

00:04:39.480 --> 00:04:42.510
which combines
analytical sophistication

00:04:42.510 --> 00:04:44.970
with a dash of playfulness.

00:04:44.970 --> 00:04:47.340
In her first book,
entitled Governing

00:04:47.340 --> 00:04:51.480
the Tongue: The Politics of
Speech in Early New England,

00:04:51.480 --> 00:04:55.080
Jane applied insights from
anthropology and linguistics

00:04:55.080 --> 00:04:58.710
to examine speech as a
way of wielding power

00:04:58.710 --> 00:05:00.930
in early America.

00:05:00.930 --> 00:05:04.410
For Jane's 2008 book,
The Exchange Artist,

00:05:04.410 --> 00:05:08.550
she drew on urban design,
architecture, and economics

00:05:08.550 --> 00:05:12.930
to tell the story of the Boston
Coffee House, at one time

00:05:12.930 --> 00:05:16.170
an important Boston
institution unique to its time

00:05:16.170 --> 00:05:18.780
and place in the early republic.

00:05:18.780 --> 00:05:21.540
Jane probes this
fascinating local site,

00:05:21.540 --> 00:05:25.020
and at the same time
she reveals its key role

00:05:25.020 --> 00:05:29.790
in the speculative capitalism
of the early American republic.

00:05:29.790 --> 00:05:34.350
In 2007, Jane received a
prestigious New Directions

00:05:34.350 --> 00:05:37.020
Grant from the Mellon
Foundation, which

00:05:37.020 --> 00:05:40.620
allowed her to train
in a totally new field

00:05:40.620 --> 00:05:43.770
to expand her
methodological toolkit.

00:05:43.770 --> 00:05:46.530
Jane used the grant to
spend a year in London,

00:05:46.530 --> 00:05:50.280
immersing herself in the
study of art history.

00:05:50.280 --> 00:05:53.910
That retooling contributed
to Jane's latest book,

00:05:53.910 --> 00:05:57.390
A Revolution in Color: The
World of John Singleton

00:05:57.390 --> 00:06:00.540
Copley, published last October.

00:06:00.540 --> 00:06:02.970
This book delves into
the artistic life

00:06:02.970 --> 00:06:05.970
and the tumultuous times
of a man best known

00:06:05.970 --> 00:06:08.940
for portraits of prominent
figures like Paul Revere

00:06:08.940 --> 00:06:11.970
and Samuel Adams in a
political revolution

00:06:11.970 --> 00:06:16.650
about which Copley himself
remained ambivalent.

00:06:16.650 --> 00:06:19.830
True to Jane's commitment
at the Schlesinger

00:06:19.830 --> 00:06:23.430
to embed considerations
of gender and family

00:06:23.430 --> 00:06:25.920
and how we tell
all of our history,

00:06:25.920 --> 00:06:30.330
her Copley story locates him
as much in the private life

00:06:30.330 --> 00:06:33.870
of his family and household
as in the public life

00:06:33.870 --> 00:06:37.510
of 18th century
imperial politics.

00:06:37.510 --> 00:06:40.390
If Copley was awash
in ambivalence

00:06:40.390 --> 00:06:42.640
about the American
Revolution, there

00:06:42.640 --> 00:06:46.210
has been nothing ambivalent
about the critical response

00:06:46.210 --> 00:06:48.400
to A Revolution in Color.

00:06:48.400 --> 00:06:51.160
It has won the American History
Book Prize of the New York

00:06:51.160 --> 00:06:54.340
Historical Society and the
Annibel Jenkins Biography

00:06:54.340 --> 00:06:58.270
Prize of the American Society
for Eighteenth-Century Studies.

00:06:58.270 --> 00:07:02.470
It was also named a finalist
for PEN's Jacqueline Bograd Weld

00:07:02.470 --> 00:07:05.230
Award for Biography,
the Marfield

00:07:05.230 --> 00:07:09.340
Prize for Arts Writing, and the
George Washington Book Prize.

00:07:09.340 --> 00:07:12.220
I am confident that we
will all benefit from

00:07:12.220 --> 00:07:16.480
and greatly enjoy learning more
about A Revolution in Color

00:07:16.480 --> 00:07:18.040
from Jane today.

00:07:18.040 --> 00:07:21.190
So now please join me
in giving a warm welcome

00:07:21.190 --> 00:07:21.935
to Jane Kamensky.

